Crimea and Sudentenland, same fight?
BRUSSELS – The Russian takeover of the Crimea constitutes the most serious example of aggression in peacetime that Europe has known since the annexation of the Sudentenland by Nazi Germany in 1938.
It is certainly a current practice to minimize the importance of the "Munich lessons" when this episode is mentioned, which saw Neville Chamberlain and Édouard Daladier accede to Hitler's demands on Czechoslovakia in order to appease the führer.
However, if the Western world were to close its eyes on the annexation of the Crimea – the second case of the invasion of a sovereign territory by Russian President Vladimir Putin, after the capture of the Georgian regions of Abkhazia and South Ossetia in 2008 – the current democratic leaders could well regret their inaction.
Within Western capitals, reactions have until now been mixed.
The sanctions currently being considered – an expulsion from the G8, for instance – could make one smile if the threat to peace in Europe were not as serious.
Putin considers the collapse of the Soviet Union as the most severe catastrophe of the modern era, the man straining tirelessly to resurrect a fallen Russian empire.
If the West wants to be taken seriously, it will have to act with the same determination that Putin displays.
The numerous successes of the Russian president within the framework of his imperialist project have cost him almost nothing up to this point.
His initiative in favor of an Eurasian Economic Community has allowed Russia to rally a certain number of resource-rich states, such as Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, and Turkmenistan.
Georgia was dismantled in 2008.
As for the Armenian government, the Russian intimidation pushed it to reject the association agreement proposed by the European Union.
And here's the most valuable geopolitical prize of all – Ukraine – which might well fall into Putin's hands.
Without Ukraine, Russia "stops being an empire," as explained by the former US national security advisor Zbigniew Brzezinski; "in contrast, with a suborned and then subordinated Ukraine, Russia becomes an empire automatically." And since the vast majority of Ukrainians aspire to join no empire of Putin's, it is very likely that the country led by the Russian president is now a highly militarized state, a kind of Soviet Union devoid of a communist party.
It is essential that the international community's reaction is commensurate with the degree of adventurism that Putin displays.
Annulations of summits, commercial agreements proposals and other participation to forums as unproductive as the G8 cannot suffice.
Only actions involving the pronouncement of tangible economic sanctions, capable of affecting Russian citizens – who, let's recall, continue to re-elect Putin to power – will allow us to hope to see the Kremlin leave its expansionist track.
What sanctions could it be?
Firstly, Turkey could decide to close the Dardanelles strait to Russian transports, as it did after the 2008 Russian-Georgian war.
At the time, Turkey had blocked access to the Black Sea in order to prevent the United States from intervening, although it now appears clearly that it was not the intention of the United States.
Today, Turkey could choose to close the Turkish straits not only to Russian warships, but also to all commercial ships heading to Russian Black Sea ports.
The impact on Russia's economy – as well as on Putin's military claims – would be considerable.
Turkey is authorized to close the Dardanelles under an amendment made in 1982 to the 1936 Montreux Convention.
Turkey could thus turn back on Putin the motive invoked by him to justify the capture of Crimea – namely that he would preserve the Russian ethnic groups living there – by claiming she would itself protect her Turkish cousins of Tatar belonging, who, considering the bad treatment suffered at the hands of Russia, clearly want to remain under Ukrainian rule.
Last week, Turkish Foreign Minister Ahmet Davutoğlu ordered his plane to make a U-turn in mid-air, in order to head to Kiev to provide support to the new interim government.
The Turkish prime minister Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, who as Putin knows is not soft either, could thus step in line with him by immediately closing the Turkish straits to Russian transports – until Putin recalls all his Crimean troops to regain their bases, namely those in Sevastopol or Russia.
It would be good if Turkey could count on the guarantee granted by Article 5 of the NATO treaty in case Russia tries to intimidate it.
Secondly, US President Barack Obama could pronounce against Russia the same type of financial sanctions he imposed on Iran around its nuclear program.
These sanctions have indeed significantly invalidated Iran's economy.
In the same way, refusing access to the American financial system to all banks doing business with Russian banking institutions or companies would allow for an unprecedented economic chaos in Russia since the fall of communism.
The Russian citizens must understand that allowing Putin – whose accession to power is based on his promise to put an end to the scarcity of the first years of the post-Soviet era – to continue his aggressive imperialist approach could cost them dearly.
Thirdly, it would be possible for Obama to remind the Chinese of their role in Eurasian stability.
A true drama in Putin's eyes, the disintegration of the Soviet Union has constituted for China the most formidable geostrategic windfall that one can imagine.
In an instant, this empire that had ravished several million hectares of Chinese territory over the centuries, and threatened the People's Republic with nuclear annihilation, simply vanished.
Since then, the independent states of Central Asia, and Ukraine itself, have become important commercial partners of China.
The invasion of Georgia by Russia has seriously displeased China, as it was evident at the Shanghai Cooperation Organization summit held after the war (this regional grouping gathering a number of ex-Soviet states with common borders with China and the motherland).
Russia has tried to have the SCO recognize the independence of Abkhazia and South Ossetia.
However, the Organization has expressed its disagreement.
Now, however, the member states of Central Asia – Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, and Uzbekistan – would have never been able to rise up against the Kremlin without Chinese support.
It now falls to Chinese President Xi Jinping to be less enigmatic in his response to Putin's bold moves.
The true test of this Chinese claim to be a true and responsible protagonist within the international community will indeed be played out very soon at the United Nations.
Will China support this blatant violation of international law committed by Putin, or will it align itself in support of Ukraine's territorial integrity?
Two other sanction options are also conceivable.
Each Russian leader could thus see their visas refused or cancelled.
It would also be possible to freeze a certain number of assets, including those that have been whitewashed by oligarchs close to Putin.
This will only be when the pain has become unbearable, and notably for the elite, that this type of kampf led by Putin today will fail.
The price of inaction may well turn out to be considerable.
Many countries, from Japan to Israel, rely on this promise of America to act with firmness against any serious threat to peace.
Furthermore, when Ukraine renounced its nuclear arsenal in 1994, it did so on the express condition that the United States (alongside the United Kingdom, France, and Russia) guarantee its territorial integrity.
If Crimea were to remain annexed, no one will blame Ukraine if it decides to re-nuclearize its defense (which it remains technologically capable of doing).
When Chamberlain returned from Munich, Winston Churchill addressed him using the famous formula: 'You had the choice between war and dishonor.'
You chose dishonor, and you will have war.'
If they were to choose the dishonor, we can be certain that the audacious Putin will eventually serve them a new war.'
